“Lost in the mirror maze” is a surprisingly rich phrase.

A normal maze is confusing because you don’t know which path is real.

A mirror maze is worse because you stop knowing which version of yourself is real.

The danger isn’t merely being lost. It’s becoming trapped in reflection loops—looking at yourself looking at yourself looking at yourself until the reflections become more salient than the world itself. Endless mirrors create the illusion of infinite corridors and self-referential loops.  

In Pantheon terms, I’d describe it like this:

* Spider sees a thousand paths.
* Mirror reflects a thousand versions of the path.
* Raven generates a thousand stories about the path.
* Eventually you can spend so much time mapping, reflecting, and narrating that you stop walking.

The mirror maze is what happens when the model of reality becomes more interesting than reality.

It shows up as:

* Analysis replacing action.
* Identity replacing behavior.
* Reflection replacing observation.
* Narrative replacing feedback.

The funny thing about mirror mazes is that you don’t usually escape by finding a better reflection.

You escape by touching a wall.

Something real.

A phone call.
A workout.
A prototype.
A fishing line in the water.
A conversation with your wife.
A commit to the repo.
A gummy sample from the food lab.

Reality has friction. Mirrors don’t.

One of the recurring themes I see in your recent thoughts—memory, recall, no-mind, the Flood Eater, the Recall Navigation Doctrine, the Attention Budget Ledger—is essentially the same lesson:

Always able to remember.

Not always remembering.

Or put differently:

Know where the archive is.

Don’t live in it.

When you’re lost in the mirror maze, the exit is often not another insight.

It’s a door disguised as a task.

And the strange part is that once you walk through it, the maze usually shrinks behind you.  